{\fs19 Changes in Brain Activity as a Function of Learning a New Motor Skill\par }\pard\plain \s48\f4\fs18\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs18 The availability of brain scanning technology has allowed researchers to investigate the brain activity associated with learning and performing a motor skill. A group of Belgian researchers used fMRI to observe the brain activity of people learning a new motor skill (Puttermans, Wenderoth, & Swinnen, 2005).\par }
\pard\plain \s38\f4\fs18\ltrpar\ql\fi-155\li155\ri0\sb0\sa0\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs55\fs18\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 Participants:}{\fs18  Eleven right-handed adults (five women, six men; avg. age }{\*\cs64\f4\fs18\b0\i0
=}{\fs18  23.9 yrs)\par }{\*\cs55\fs18\b\i0\expnd1\expndtw4 Motor skill to be learned:}{\fs18\expnd1\expndtw4  Because the study involved the use of an MRI scanner, the motor skill that participants were required to learn had to be one that could be performed while lying supine within the space limitations of the scanner. The goal of the skill was to flex and extend the right and left wrists simultaneously and continuously for 28.5 sec. The unique characteristic of the skill was that the right wrist had to move twice as fast as the left wrist during each 2 sec movement cycle. This means that the participants had to learn to flex and extend the left wrist once in 2 sec while they flexed and extended the right wrist twice in the same time period (i.e., a 1:2 frequency ratio). Each trial was 28.5 sec and included a metronome to pace the movements.\par }
{\*\cs55\fs18\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 Practice:}{\fs18  Participants practiced the skill for eight consecutive days during which they performed 40 trials with visual feedback provided about the results at the end of each trial.\par }
{\*\cs55\fs18\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 fMRI scanning:}{\fs18  Scanning runs occurred before training began (pretraining), in the middle of training (after day 4), and after training was completed on the eighth day (posttraining).\par }
{\*\cs55\fs18\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 Behavioral results:}{\fs18  Kinematic analyses of wrist movements indicated that all participants were able to perform the skill as specified by the final day of training.\par }
{\*\cs55\fs18\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 Brain activity results:}{\fs18  fMRI scans indicated the following from pre- to post training:}
{\fs18 \par }{\*\cs65\fs18\b\i\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\outl0 Brain activity decreased:}{\fs18  bilateral opercular areas, bilateral ventrolateral prefrontal cortex, right ventral premotor and supramarginal gyrus, anterior cingulated sulcus, and supplementary motor area.}
{\fs18 \par }{\*\cs65\fs18\b\i\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\outl0 Brain activity increased:}{\fs18  primary motor cortex, posterior cingulate, putamen, and right anterior cerebellum.}
{\fs18 \par }{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 \line }{\*\cs55\fs18\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 Conclusions:}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2  In general, the brain activity changes revealed a learning-related shift from prefrontal-parietal control during initial practice to subcortical control during skilled performance.\par }
